@dlyle65535 I added the proposed changes and it almost works.  Running an individual role worked as expected but when I run "vagrant destroy -f" I get:  

Message: GetoptLong::InvalidOption: invalid option -- f.  

We probably want to still allow other vagrant options to be passed in.  Any ideas?

@merrimanr Hmm, I liked that feature (being able to run individual roles against either a vagrant image or a prebuilt image).  That will be useful, I think for letting people get metron and try stuff out on it.

Actually, now that I think about it, I'm not sure this should be a vagrant-specific thing.  I think the original approach was general to ansible which makes more sense since we also have an ec2 deployment that it'd be nice to include support for.

Thoughts?

No specific ideas on the -f issue. I can work on it a bit Sunday or Monday. Of course, everything should work when it's over including a pre-built snapshot. I'd just prefer we use the existing Vagrant capability for VM Provider -> Provisioner handoff. 

@cestella - I think we're good on a generic solution, just use the regular ansible-playbook command with --tags and/or --skip-tags. I don't really see any reason to abstract that. Not abstracting it has a lot of advantages: it's well documented by Ansible, anyone with a background in Ansible already knows about it, we don't have to maintain it- stuff like that. In my opinion, our Vagrant provisioning is the oddball here as we currently have to modify the Vagrantfile to leverage tags. That's why I'm recommending that we do something specific in the Vagrantfile to expose those arguments.

All that said, I'm happy to include the script as well. Though I don't agree that run_enrichment_role.sh is more intuitive than doing it using Vagrant and/or ansible-playbook. Mostly for the reasons stated above.  Though, I probably should have suggested the arguments for Vagrant be --tags and --skip-tags to make it consistent.
